> Curries are one of those meals that warms your heart and your belly—for Asian Heritage Month, try this vegetarian version that's no exception! Chickpeas, onion, and bell pepper get a super savory treatment in a coconut-based curry sauce. Serve it over rice, add a dollop of yogurt and a sprinkle of cilantro, and you have yourself one soul-satisfying meal.

== Rice ==

Wash and dry produce.

Peel and mince @garlic{1%clove}. Halve, peel, and finely dice @onion{1}(diced).

Drain and rinse @chickpeas{1%can}. Finely chop @cilantro{1/4%ounce}.

Melt @butter{1%tbsp} in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Add half the
garlic and cook until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Add @basmati rice{1/2%cup}, 3/4 cup water, and a big pinch of @salt{}.
Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce heat to low. Cook until rice is
tender, ~{15-18%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

== Curry ==

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tsp} in a #medium pot{} over medium-high
heat. Add @bell pepper{1}(deseeded and finely diced) and onion;
cook until softened and lightly browned, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Stir in @tomato paste{1}, @curry powder{1%tbsp}, @paprika{1%tsp},
@garam masala{1/2%tsp}, and remaining garlic until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

> TIP: Love the earthy warmth of garam masala? Add more if you like!

Stir in chickpeas, @coconut milk{1}, @veggie stock concentrate{1},
1/4 cup water, and @sugar{1/2%tsp}. Bring to a simmer, then reduce heat
to low; cook until thickened, stirring occasionally, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> TIP: If curry seems too thick, stir in a splash of water.

Remove from heat; stir in @butter{1%tbsp} until melted. Season generously
with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

== To Serve ==

Fluff rice with a #fork{}; season with salt and pepper.

Divide rice between bowls. Top with curry. Dollop with @yogurt{2%tbsp}.

Garnish with cilantro and serve.